   "hider_text": "The room breathes in slow waves. Dust motes float in the hush between the ceiling and the floorboards, caught in the pull of a dim light that doesn’t quite reach the corners. There’s a sound beneath the silence—a soft hum, like a string just below the surface of water. It doesn’t come from any instrument, but the air itself seems to vibrate with a memory / The metal frame hums at the edge of sleep. It’s not loud, just a low tremor in the floorboards, like the bones of a sleeping animal. The rust on the side isn’t red—it’s a tired brown, like old leather left in the sun. You can feel it just beneath your thoughts, a coolness that doesn’t belong to the air.  \n\nThere’s a / The sand remembers the shape of a hand pressed into it.  \nNot the hand of a person—no, not that—something older. Something that once moved with the wind, slow and sure, like a breath held too long.  \n\nThere’s a place where the ground cracks in a pattern that looks like a map, not of paths, but of breaths. The cracks are dry, but",
   "seeker_text": "The smell of rain on hot pavement. Not the wet kind, not the cool kind—this is the one that happens just after the sun has burned off the morning fog, when the sky opens up and the air hangs thick with the scent of oil, dust, and something green underneath. It’s a sharp, metallic tang that doesn’t belong to any single thing. It’s the smell of a / The smell of wet wool under a winter sun.  \n\nNot the kind you find in a store, or on a coat left in a drawer. This is the smell of a woolen sweater — thick, unspun, still damp from being folded and left outside overnight. It’s not sharp or clean. It’s earthy, like soil after rain, with a faint hint of old wood and / The smell of wet earth after a summer rain.  \nNot the kind from a garden, not the kind from a driveway, but from a long, slow downpour that seeped through the roots of an old oak in the corner of the woods behind the house. It wasn’t just damp soil—it was the deep, slow breath of the ground itself, releasing minerals and decay and something ancient,"
  },
