  {
   "round": 4,
   "hider_text": "The salt in the air settles on the back of the throat like old paper.  \n\nIt gathers in the hollows of the morning—between the stones, behind the roots of the oak that leans over the path. You don’t walk there often. The ground is soft with damp moss, and the way the light curls through the leaves feels like a slow breath.  \n\nA wind comes from the east",
   "seeker_text": "The way your reflection in a window shifts just before you turn your head—how the light bends slightly, the edges of your face blur for a split second, like a photograph being reassembled in real time. It doesn’t happen to you. It happens *around* you. And when you catch it, you don’t know if you’re seeing yourself or the glass remembering you.",
