  {
   "round": 5,
   "hider_text": "The salt in the air settles like dust on the windowpane. Not from the sea, not exactly—no, that’s too loud, too direct—but from somewhere older, somewhere behind the wind that hums through the cracks in the old barn. It tastes on the tongue when you bite into the crust of bread baked too long in the oven. It’s in the way the light hits the metal",
   "seeker_text": "The exact weight of a folded paper airplane sitting in your palm—just before you toss it. Not the paper, not the motion, but the stillness of it in your hand: light, fragile, holding its breath. It doesn’t feel like a thing that will fly. It feels like a thought that hasn’t yet left the body.",
