  {
   "round": 7,
   "hider_text": "The salt hangs in the air like dust after a storm. It coats the inside of the glass, the back of the throat — a thin film, not wet, just *there*.  \n\nA room with no windows. The walls are old plaster, cracked at the corners, smelling of dried wood and something older — like the skin of a tree that has been left in the dark. The floor is",
   "seeker_text": "The exact second your phone screen turns off—when the light fades not from power loss, but from a kind of surrender, like the screen finally stops trying to show you the world. The silence after the last pixel dies isn’t empty. It’s full of the space where color used to live. And for a breath, you don’t reach for it. You just wait.",
